{'project_name': 'Adjusted Water Management in Rice Cultivation In Dawu County', 'project_summary': 'The project changing from continuously flooded to intermittent flooded condition during rice cultivation is conducted in Dawu County within Xiaogan City, Hubei Province of China, with a total acreage of 13,430 ha for single-cropping rice. Without the implementation of this project, which provides ditches to conduct intermittently flooded method, the continuously flooded method would be continued, so the scenario that rice was cultivated by continuously flooded method is the baseline scenario. Since the organic matter in rice soil under flooded condition can emit a large amount of methane (CH4) because of anaerobic decomposition, the intermittent flooded method is more beneficial to water conservation, production increase and methane emission reduction than the continuously flooded.
This project solved the problems of excessive water used during rice cultivation which results in not only large amount of methane (CH4) emissions but also low rice productivity by replacing the continuously flooded method with intermittent flooded method, which shortens the period of anaerobic decomposition of soil organic matter. In this case, the CH4 emission can be declined by an average of 48%1 . Hence, with the proposed project activity, an estimated amount of GHG emission reduction 4.46 tCO2e/ha for single-cropping rice is expected.
The implementation of the project is expected to reduce the GHG emissions amounting to 419,461 tCO2e in the first 7 years, with an average annual GHG emission removal of 59,923tCO2e.
This project aims to:
- Sequester greenhouse gas and mitigate climate changes;
- Increase the rice productivity resulting in higher living standard of local farmers;
- Provide more job opportunities, especially women workers;
- Use a proportion of benefits to improve the local children’s education.', 'project_state_province': 'Hubei Province', 'project_country': 'China', 'project_latitude': 31.32, 'project_longitude': 114.07}

{'project_name': 'Adjusted Water Management in Rice Cultivation in Jiangyou City', 'project_summary': 'The project changing from continuously flooded to intermittent flooded condition during rice cultivation is conducted in Jiangyou City within Mianyang City, Sichuan Province of China, with a total acreage of 16,121 ha for single-cropping rice. Without the implementation of this project, the continuously flooded method would be continued, so the scenario that rice was cultivated by continuously flooded method is the baseline scenario. Since the organic matter in rice soil under flooded condition can emit a large amount of methane (CH4) because of anaerobic decomposition, the intermittent flooded method is more beneficial to water conservation, production increase and methane emission reduction than the continuously flooded.
This project solved the problems of excessive water used during rice cultivation which results in not only large amount of methane (CH4) emissions but also low rice productivity by replacing the continuously flooded method with intermittent flooded method, which shortens the period of anaerobic decomposition of soil organic matter. In this case, the CH4 emission can be declined by an average of 48%1 . Hence, with the proposed project activity, an estimated amount of GHG emission reduction 3.55 tCO2e/ha for single-cropping rice is expected. Annual average estimation of GHG emission reductions from the project activity is 57,281 tCO2e/year, and the total GHG emission reductions are 572,810 tCO2e during the fixed 10 years crediting period.
This project aims to:
- Sequester greenhouse gas and mitigate climate changes;
- Increase the rice productivity resulting in higher living standard of local farmers;
- Increase in the number of individuals who have relevant skills due to diversified educational opportunities from Trainings;
- Provide more job opportunities, especially women workers.', 'project_state_province': 'Sichuan Province', 'project_country': 'China', 'project_latitude': 31.55, 'project_longitude': 104.53}
